## §Cadence Rule 2 (continued) — Retroactive-Close Precondition

An **orphan-impl issue** (issue for which the fix already exists in working-tree but no PR has been opened) can be retroactively closed **ONLY IF** BOTH preconditions are verified:

1. **(a) PR-persistence**: the fix is PR-persisted in `origin/main` (NOT just local working-tree).
   Verification: `git fetch origin main && git show origin/main:<file>` MUST contain the fix.
2. **(b) Closes anchor**: that PR body contains an ADR-0057 strict `Closes #<N>` anchor referencing the issue.

**Retroactive close WITHOUT an anchor-PR is INVALID**; the issue MUST be reopened.

**Restart-survivability test** (mandatory before retroactive close):

```bash
git fetch origin main
git show origin/main:<file> | grep -F '<expected fix line>'
```

If the grep returns 0 lines → the fix is NOT in main → retroactive close forbidden → reopen + dispatch architect/tester/developer chain.

## §Why this clause

In cycle ~#2776, Cadence Rule 2 amendment was applied (forward-port dispatch on ADR merge) but the symmetric retroactive-close case (close orphan-impl without a PR) was NOT preconditioned. At cycle ~#~12:56 UTC, the gap surfaced as: AtilCalculator #1128 + #1129 were retroactively closed without a PR, only the working-tree had the fix, and the bug came back live after tmux restart (10:32 UTC, all 5 panes `--agent not found`). Owner directive cycle ~#~12:56Z mandated this clause.

